These graphs show the distribution and proportion of our variables to get an idea of normality and explore more into our variables.

Our DV stoke variable is comprised of a majority of non stroke patients.

Our IVs numerical: BMI is fairly normally distributed with it slightly skewed to the right. Glucose level is less normally distributed and more skewed to the right. Our age range is vast from 0-80. It looks somewhat normal.

Our IVs categorical: Female-Male distribution is fairly even with a tad more females than males in our dataset. Hypertension and heart disease has much more patients without. There are more patients that are ever married than not. about 2:1. Worktype: Most patients are recorded as private. Residence type: THis variable is fairly even with slight more in urban areas. smoking status: The highest datapoint is never smoked and then smokes + former smoked are roughly the same. There is a lot of unknown smoking status here too.

chi-square test for initial selection for categorical IVs

#DV vs. categorical IVs

stroke_gender_tb <- table(df$stroke, df$gender)

stroke_hypertension_tb <- table(df$stroke, df$hypertension)

stroke_hd_tb <- table(df$stroke, df$heart_disease)

stroke_married_tb <- table(df$stroke, df$ever_married)

stroke_work_tb <- table(df$stroke, df$work_type)

stroke_Residence_tb <- table(df$stroke, df$Residence_type)

stroke_Smoking_tb <- table(df$stroke, df$smoking_status)
chisq.test(stroke_gender_tb)
## Warning in chisq.test(stroke_gender_tb): Chi-squared approximation may be

## incorrect
## 

##  Pearson's Chi-squared test

## 

## data:  stroke_gender_tb

## X-squared = 0.47259, df = 2, p-value = 0.7895

p-value>0.05 do not reject H0, i.e.gender has no effect on stroke

chisq.test(stroke_hypertension_tb)
## 

##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction

## 

## data:  stroke_hypertension_tb

## X-squared = 81.605, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16

p-value<0.05 we can reject H0, i.e.hypertension has an effect on stroke

## 

##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction

p-value<0.05 we can reject H0, i.e.heart disease has an effect on stroke

t-test or Mann-Whitney U test for initial selection for continuous IVs

#Normality Assumption

groups <- split(df$bmi,df$stroke)

shapiro_results <- lapply(groups, shapiro.test)

p_values <- sapply(shapiro_results, function(x) x$p.value)

p_values
##            0            1 

## 9.811863e-38 6.427205e-10

both groups have p-value<0.05 then we can reject H0 , i.e.the 2 groups are different which suggests that bmi has an impact on the response variable

#Mann-whiteny U test

mwu_result <- wilcox.test(df$bmi, df$stroke)

mwu_result
## 

##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction

## 

## data:  df$bmi and df$stroke

## W = 26112100, p-value < 2.2e-16

## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

p-value<0.05 then we can reject H0 , i.e.bmi has an impact on the response variable

Classification table for the simple model (no interaction)

model <- glm(stroke ~ age + hypertension + avg_glucose_level, data = train, family = binomial)

pred <- predict(model, newdata = test, type = "response")

pred_class <- ifelse(pred > 0.04872798, 1, 0)

classification_table <- table(actual = test$stroke, predicted = pred_class)

classification_table
##       predicted

## actual   0   1

##      0 731 235

##      1  17  39
TP <- classification_table[2,2]

FP <- classification_table[1,2]

TN <- classification_table[1,1]

FN <- classification_table[2,1]



sensitivity <- TP / (TP + FN)

specificity <- TN / (TN + FP)

accuracy <- (TP + TN)/ (TP + FN + TN + FP)



header <- c("sensitivity","specificity","accuracy")

values <- c(sensitivity,specificity,accuracy)

percentg <- c(paste(round(sensitivity*100,2),"%"),paste(round(specificity*100,2),"%"),paste(round(accuracy*100,2),"%"))



result = data.frame(header,values,percentg)

Lack-of-fit test

Hosmer-Lemeshow goodness-of-fit on the reduced model

Test the goodness of fit of the reduced model on test data

#H0: Model is a good fit for the test data

#H1: Model is not a good fit for the test data

model <- glm(stroke ~ age + hypertension + avg_glucose_level, data = test, family = binomial)



library(ResourceSelection)
## Warning: package 'ResourceSelection' was built under R version 4.2.3
## ResourceSelection 0.3-5   2019-07-22
probs <- predict(model, newdata = test, type = "response")

hoslem.test(test$stroke, probs, g=10)
## 

##  Hosmer and Lemeshow goodness of fit (GOF) test

## 

## data:  test$stroke, probs

## X-squared = 9.5733, df = 8, p-value = 0.2963

On train data

#H0: Model is a good fit for the training data

#H1: Model is not a good fit for the training data

model <- glm(stroke ~ age + hypertension + avg_glucose_level, data = train, family = binomial)



library(ResourceSelection)

probs <- predict(model, newdata = train, type = "response")

hoslem.test(train$stroke, probs, g=10)
## 

##  Hosmer and Lemeshow goodness of fit (GOF) test

## 

## data:  train$stroke, probs

## X-squared = 4.5598, df = 8, p-value = 0.8034

p-value > 0.05, no lack of fit.

The large p-value indicates that our p-value is statistically insignificant therefore we do not have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis. Thus, we can claim that there is not evidence to say that our model is not a good fit.

on train data

#H0: Model is a good fit for the training data

#H1: Model is not a good fit for the training data

library(ResourceSelection)

## 

##  Hosmer and Lemeshow goodness of fit (GOF) test

## 

## data:  train$stroke, probs

## X-squared = 11.109, df = 8, p-value = 0.1956

From the Hosmer-Lemeshow tests, we can conclude that both the reduced model and the reduced model with interaction are good fit to predict a stroke for a person.

However, as the Hosmer-Lemeshow test is not the best method to validate our model due to our relatively small sample size, we will conduct other statistical test which is the deviance goodness of fit test or the likelihood test. This test is also robust to small sample size which is suitable to assess our model.

Pseudo R-squared

Reduced model

model <- glm(factor(stroke) ~ age + factor(hypertension) + avg_glucose_level, data = train, family = binomial)

nullDeviance     <- model$null.deviance 

residualDeviance <- model$deviance      

pseudoRSquared   <- 1 - (residualDeviance/nullDeviance)



print(pseudoRSquared)
## [1] 0.199497

Our model only explains ~19.9% of the deviance, which means that we havent yet identified all the factors that predict whether or not a person will get stroke.

Model with interaction

model_full <- glm(factor(stroke) ~ age + factor(hypertension) + avg_glucose_level + factor(smoking_status):bmi, data = train, family = "binomial")



nullDeviance     <- model_full$null.deviance 

residualDeviance <- model_full$deviance      

pseudoRSquared   <- 1 - (residualDeviance/nullDeviance)



print(pseudoRSquared)
## [1] 0.2010341

Our model only explains ~20.1% of the deviance, which means that we havent yet identified all the factors that predict whether or not a person will get stroke.

Statistically speaking, the values shows that the full model is the better fit.

However, accounting the result acquired from the likelihood ratio test we conducted before which shows that the reduced model is actually the better fit as well as looking at the relatively small difference (0.2%) between and reduced model and the model with interaction, we decided to conduct another lack of fit test by doing a cross validation.

Cross Validation

Reduced Model

formula <- factor(stroke) ~ age + factor(hypertension) + avg_glucose_level



# Define the training control for 10-fold cross-validation

train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)



# Train the model using logistic regression and 10-fold cross-validation

model <- train(formula, data = train, method = "glm", family = "binomial", trControl = train_control)



# Print the results

print(model)

##

##   0.9527906  0

Model with interaction

formula <- factor(stroke) ~ age + factor(hypertension) + avg_glucose_level + factor(smoking_status):bmi



# Define the training control for 10-fold cross-validation

train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

##   0.9527895  0

The reduced model shows a slightly higher accuracy (0.0000011) compared to the model with interaction, as the difference is very small we believe that the simpler model is more preferable. This is because simpler models are easier for interpretation and understanding, as well as having lesser likelihood to overfit.
